Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
addNet(25.10)                                                    addNet(25.10)

Name
       addNet - Adds a net to the design

Syntax
       addNet

       [-help]

       <netName>

       [-bus <startID>:<endID>]

       [-moduleBased <verilogModule>]

       [-power  | -ground ]

       Adds a net to the design. The net can be logical or physical.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each addNet parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the  man  command:

              man addNet

       -bus <startID>:<endID>
              Specifies the bit range for bus nets. The <startID> and  <endID>
              indicate  the  first and last bits on the bus. You must separate
              the start and end IDs with a colon (:).

              If the specified bus does not exist, tool will create  a  bussed
              Verilog net.

              If the specified bus already exists, tool will do bus net resiz-
              ing.  The  specified bus bit range must be adjacent to the first
              or last bit of the existing bus. Also, it must have the same as-
              cending or descending order as existing bus.

              Note: PG bus net is not supported

              -ground" Adds a ground net.

       -moduleBased <verilogModule>
              Adds the new net to the specified verilog module.

              If the module name contains  special  characters,  you  need  to
              start  the  module  name  with a backslash '\' and end it with a
              space.

       <netName>
              Specifies the net to add.

              If the net name contains special characters, you need  to  start
              the  part  of  the  net name, which contains special characters,
              with a backslash '\' and end it with a space.

              Note: You must specify <netName> before you specify other  para-
              meters. The software issues an error message if you do not spec-
              ify the <netName> first.

       -power Adds a power net.

Examples
              * The following command adds net i1/n1:

                addNet -name i1/n1

              *

                The  following  command  adds one bit i1/n1[6] to existing bus
                i1/n1[2:5]:

                addNet -name i1/n1 -bus 6:6

              *

                The following command adds  three  bits  i1/n1[-1],  i1/n1[0],
                i1/n1[1] to existing bus i1/n1[2:5]:

                addNet -name i1/n1 -bus -1:1

              * The following command adds net with base name ant_net to hier-
                archy DTMF_INST/TDSP_CORE_INST/TDSP_CORE_MACH_INST[0].g:

                addNet                                                   -name
                {DTMF_INST/TDSP_CORE_INST/\TDSP_CORE_MACH_INST[0].g /ant_net}

                Here the "[" and "]" brackets between the  backslash  and  the
                space are special characters.

              * The    following    command    adds   net   with   base   name
                TDSP_CORE_INST/TDSP_CORE_MATCH_INST[0].g/ant_net to  hierarchy
                DTMF_INST:

                addNet                                                   -name
                {DTMF_INST/\TDSP_CORE_INST/TDSP_CORE_MATCH_INST[0].g  /ant_net
                }

              * The  following  command  adds net with base name ant_net[1] to
                module H[1]:

                addNet -name {\ant_net[1] } -moduleBased {\H[1] }

